CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Human Relations – Violations of County Discrimination Laws – Complaints
3 FOR the purpose of establishing that filing a certain complaint with the Maryland
4 Commission on Civil Rights satisfies certain prerequisites to commencing a civil
5 action alleging the violation of a county discrimination law; and generally relating
6 to county discrimination laws.
7 BY repealing and reenacting, without amendments,
8 Article – State Government
9 Section 20–1004(a) and (c)
10 Annotated Code of Maryland
11 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
12 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
13 Article – State Government
14 Section 20–1202 and 20–1203
15 Annotated Code of Maryland
16 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
17 BY adding to
18 Article – State Government
19 Section 20–1204
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *sb0694*

2 SENATE BILL 694
1 Annotated Code of Maryland
2 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
3 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
4 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
5 Article – State Government
6 20–1004.
7 (a) Any person claiming to be aggrieved by an alleged discriminatory act may file
8 a complaint with the Commission.
9 (c) (1) (i) Except as provided in paragraphs (2) and (3) of this subsection, a
10 complaint shall be filed within 6 months after the date on which the alleged discriminatory
11 act occurred.
12 (ii) A complaint filed with a federal or local human relations
13 commission within 6 months after the date on which the alleged discriminatory act occurred
14 shall be deemed to have complied with subparagraph (i) of this paragraph.
15 (2) (i) A complaint alleging an unlawful employment practice other
16 than harassment shall be filed within 300 days after the date on which the alleged
17 discriminatory act occurred.
18 (ii) A complaint filed with a federal human relations commission
19 within 6 months or a local human relations commission within 300 days shall be deemed
20 to have complied with subparagraph (i) of this paragraph.
21 (3) (i) A complaint alleging harassment against an employer shall be
22 filed within 2 years after the date on which the alleged harassment occurred.
23 (ii) A complaint filed with a federal human relations commission
24 within 6 months or a local human relations commission within 2 years after the date on
25 which the alleged harassment occurred shall be deemed to have complied with
26 subparagraph (i) of this paragraph.
27 20–1202.
28 (a) This section applies only in Howard County, Montgomery County, and Prince
29 George’s County.
30 (b) In accordance with this section, a person that is subjected to a discriminatory
31 act prohibited by the county code may bring and maintain a civil action against the person
32 that committed the alleged discriminatory act for damages, injunctive relief, or other civil
33 relief.

SENATE BILL 694 3
1 (c) (1) An action under subsection (b) of this section shall be commenced in the
2 circuit court for the county in which the alleged discriminatory act occurred within 2 years
3 after the occurrence of the alleged discriminatory act.
4 (2) (i) Subject to paragraph (1) of this subsection, an action under
5 subsection (b) of this section alleging discrimination in employment or public
6 accommodations may not be commenced sooner than 45 days after the aggrieved person
7 files a complaint with:
8 1. the county unit responsible for handling violations of the
9 county discrimination laws; OR
10 2. THE COMMISSION, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 20–1004
11 OF THIS TITLE.
12 (ii) Subject to paragraph (1) of this subsection, an action under
13 subsection (b) of this section alleging discrimination in real estate may be commenced at
14 any time.
15 (d) In a civil action under this section, the court may award the prevailing party
16 reasonable attorney’s fees, expert witness fees, and costs.
17 20–1203.
18 (a) This section applies only in Baltimore County.
19 (b) In accordance with this section, a person that is employed by an employer with
20 fewer than 15 employees and that is subjected to a discriminatory act prohibited by the
21 county code may bring and maintain a civil action against the employer that committed the
22 alleged discriminatory act for relief as provided under subsection (d) of this section.
23 (c) (1) An action under subsection (b) of this section shall be commenced in the
24 Circuit Court for Baltimore County within 2 years after the occurrence of the alleged
25 discriminatory act.
26 (2) Subject to paragraph (1) of this subsection, an action under subsection
27 (b) of this section may not be commenced sooner than 60 days after the aggrieved person
28 files a complaint with:
29 (I) the county unit responsible for handling violations of the county
30 discrimination laws; OR
31 (II) THE COMMISSION, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 20–1004 OF
32 THIS TITLE.

4 SENATE BILL 694
1 (d) (1) In a civil action under this section, the court may award the prevailing
2 party:
3 (i) injunctive relief;
4 (ii) compensatory damages, including back pay; or
5 (iii) both injunctive relief and compensatory damages.
6 (2) A prevailing party may not be awarded punitive damages under this
7 section.
8 (3) The court may award the prevailing party reasonable attorney’s fees.
9 20–1204.
10 (A) THIS SECTION APPLIES IN ANY COUNTY OTHER THAN BALTIMORE
11 COUNTY, HOWARD COUNTY, MONTGOMERY COUNTY, OR PRINCE GEORGE’S
12 COUNTY.
13 (B) A COMPLAINT FILED IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 20–1004 OF THIS TITLE
14 SATISFIES ANY REQUIREMENT TO EXHAUST REMEDIES BEFORE FILING A CIVIL
15 ACTION IMPOSED BY A COUNTY OR LOCAL UNIT RESPONSIBLE FOR HANDLING
16 VIOLATIONS OF COUNTY OR LOCAL DISCRIMINATION LAWS.
17 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
18 October 1, 2026.
Approved:
